why not params.roleId?
params.enabled?

Because we need roleId to be optional, (with the default being User), but in later code it's not optional.  I figured handling the deffault on line 1753 is what we did before, so doing it again made sense.

Same answer as roleId, even though it's optional to a user, it's required later.  We populate it on line 1759.

The point of the struct was to encapsulate the arguments required to create a user, not the arguments required by the json payload;  I guess we could invert it, and put some "not populated" safety checks inside the code later, but this seemed better.

It's subjective, if you think we should change the struct to include optionals, I'm happy to make that change.  Subjectively I think this is better, but it's a very fine line, and I'm open to feedaback.
